content.text:
The issue was that `callbackFlow` chained with `timeout` would swallow exceptions when closed with an error. This happened because the `timeout` operator's implementation in `Delay.kt` was using `values.onReceiveCatching` and handling `onClosed` by simply returning `false` (stopping the loop) without checking if the channel was closed with an exception.

I fixed this by checking if `onClosed` provides an exception (cause) and rethrowing it if present. This ensures that upstream exceptions are correctly propagated to the downstream flow.

The fix was applied in `kotlinx-coroutines-core/common/src/flow/operators/Delay.kt`.

Verified the fix with a reproduction test case (which failed before the fix and passed after) and ran existing tests in `TimeoutTest.kt` to ensure no regressions.

```kotlin
// kotlinx-coroutines-core/common/src/flow/operators/Delay.kt

// ... inside timeoutInternal ...
        values.onReceiveCatching { value ->
            value.onSuccess {
                downStream.emit(it)
            }.onClosed {
                it?.let { throw it } // Added this line to propagate exception
                return@onReceiveCatching false
            }
            return@onReceiveCatching true
        }
// ...
```

